DOE reservation, and plant personnel are protected, regardless of the cause or nature of the
accident.  Therefore, the EP addresses both radiological and non-radiological emergencies as
well as potential emergencies arising out of activities at the site that are not regulated by the
NRC.  Emergency Plan elements include:

     a general description of the plant and the surrounding area;
     accidents and the emergencies for which protective actions may be needed;
     accident detection and classification;
     policies and procedures;
     notification of and communication with plant, local governments, and regulatory agencies
     in the event of an emergency;
     coordination of the emergency response activities of both on-site and off-site response
     organizations;
     responsibilities of the key individuals and organizations involved in emergency response
     activities;
     mitigation and consequences analyses of an emergency;
     maintenance of emergency response equipment, facilities, and capabilities;
     training and exercises;
     restoration of plant equipment and systems to safe condition after an accident; and
     topics required under 10 CFR 76.91.  

The EP is maintained and updated by USEC in accordance with 10 CFR 76.91(o) and EPCRA. 
As such, USEC may change the EP without receiving prior NRC approval, provided the change
does not decrease the effectiveness of the EP and the NRC and affected offsite response
organizations are provided with copies of any changes to the EP.

Memorandums of Understanding have been implemented between the OSHA, the NRC, and the
EPA to ensure regulatory compliance and safe performance.  

